You need to download and compile the following libraries:

---------------------------------------------------------
Boost:
http://www.boost.org/

Boost is a bit tricky to compile in Cray. Below are Ilja's
instructions on how to do it.

First download and uncompress Boost.

cd <boost dir>
./bootstrap.sh
echo "using mpi : : <find-shared-library>mpich ;" >> ./tools/build/v2/user-config.jam

The next step depends on which compiler you want to use. 
NOTE: You may want to have a better control on where Boost 
headers and libs are installed. ./bjam --help

GCC:
echo "using gcc : : : <compileflags>-I/opt/mpt/default/xt/mpich2-gnu/include <linkflags>-L/opt/mpt/default/xt/mpich2-gnu/lib ;" >> ./tools/build/v2/user-config.jam
./bjam --prefix=$HOME
./bjam install --prefix=$HOME

INTEL:
echo "using intel : : : <compileflags>-I/opt/mpt/default/xt/mpich2-gnu/include <linkflags>-L/opt/mpt/default/xt/mpich2-gnu/lib ;" >> ./tools/build/v2/user-config.jam
./bjam --prefix=$HOME toolset=intel
./bjam install --prefix=$HOME toolset=intel

PGI:
echo "using pgi : : : <compileflags>-I/opt/mpt/default/xt/mpich2-gnu/include <linkflags>-L/opt/mpt/default/xt/mpich2-gnu/lib ;" >> ./tools/build/v2/user-config.jam
./bjam --prefix=$HOME toolset=pgi
./bjam install --prefix=$HOME toolset=pgi

---------------------------------------------------------
DCCRG:
http://git.berlios.de/cgi-bin/gitweb.cgi?p=dccrg;a=summary

This is the distributed MPI grid by Ilja Honkonen. Just a few headers 
and examples, compiling is not necessary.

---------------------------------------------------------
SILO:
https://wci.llnl.gov/codes/silo/

File format used to write data. Silo files can be opened directly
with VisIt visualization tool. Follow Silo's instructions for 
installing.

---------------------------------------------------------
ZOLTAN:
http://www.cs.sandia.gov/Zoltan/

Library for distributed load balancing.

---------------------------------------------------------

Finally, you need to set some paths to Makefiles. 

Makefile:

First line, set the include directive to include the file for 
your compiler of choice, options are Makefile.gcc, Makefile.intel 
and Makefile.pgi

INSTALL Set this variable to point to the directory where the 
source code is to be compiled. If you got this wrong, the make 
will complain about not being able to set symbolic links.

Then, you need to set paths to compiler-specific files, e.g. 
Makefile.gcc

You need to set Boost, Silo, Zoltan and dccrg include and lib paths.

> make main

